<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-08-09T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-08-09T02:00:00-05:00" n="843" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d843">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">894.001H61/77: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-09T15:00:00+08:00">August 9, 1935—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received August 9—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>408. Legation’s 406. Following from American Consul General at
                            Shanghai.</p>
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                            <p>“August 8, 2 p.m. Referring to my telegram of August 7, 4 p.m.
                                Japanese Vice Consul called today with the suggestion that I should
                                write to the Chairman of the Municipal Council and request the
                                police to suppress the copies of <hi rend="italic">Vanity Fair</hi>
                                that have been delivered and to prevent the sale of other copies. I
                                informed Terasaki that I did not consider that this could be done
                                and at the same time protect American interests.”</p>
                        </quote>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>